      <h2>Signs Your Formby Boiler or Cylinder Needs Attention</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Do not wait for the annual reminder if your boiler or heating system is showing any of these signs.</p>
      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Boiler making unusual noises across the heating system</strong><p>In a larger Formby property with a system boiler and multiple zones, banging, kettling or gurgling can originate from the boiler itself or from the wider heating circuit. Our service identifies the source.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Some zones heating but others not</strong><p>In a multi-zone system, partial failures indicate zone valve or motorised valve problems. These components are checked at the annual service. Identifying a sticking valve before it fails completely avoids an emergency call-out.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Hot water pressure falling in upstairs bathrooms</strong><p>For unvented cylinder properties, falling hot water pressure indicates a failing pressure reducing valve or a cylinder fault. This requires investigation by a G3 qualified engineer.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Pressure relief valve discharging</strong><p>If the pressure relief valve on your unvented cylinder is releasing water, the system pressure is exceeding safe limits. This is a fault requiring immediate investigation by a G3 qualified engineer. Do not ignore a discharging PRV.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Yellow or orange boiler flame</strong><p>A healthy gas flame is blue. Yellow or orange indicates incomplete combustion and potential CO risk. Stop using the boiler immediately. Call Cadent Gas on 0800 111 999 if you suspect a gas emergency, then call us.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>More than 12 months since the last service</strong><p>For a Formby home with a complex heating system running harder over winter, an annual service is particularly important. An unmonitored system with a failing component will typically fail at the worst possible time.</p></div></div>
